Construction SHALL NOT start background execution.

---

# 9. Start Embedded Services

Embedded services SHALL start in dependency order.

Each service SHALL report:

* Started
* Failed

Startup SHALL stop immediately upon unrecoverable failure.

---

# 10. Load Bundles

The Bundle Service SHALL:

* discover installed Bundles;
* verify Bundle integrity;
* rebuild Bundle registry.

Invalid Bundles SHALL be marked unavailable.

The Hypervisor SHALL continue startup if valid Bundles remain.

---

# 11. Restore Endpoints

The Endpoint Service SHALL:

* restore Endpoint definitions;
* restore Configuration Snapshots;
* restore publication policies;
* restore validation settings.

Endpoint restoration SHALL NOT start Providers.

---

# 12. Start Providers

The Runtime Manager SHALL:

* discover required Providers;
* initialize Providers;
* restore warm Endpoints;
* perform optional Provider warm-up.

Providers SHALL report Health before becoming available.

---

# 13. Health Verification

The Hypervisor SHALL verify:

* database connectivity;
* Provider availability;
* Scheduler readiness;
* Resource Manager readiness;
* Event Bus responsiveness.

Only healthy services SHALL participate in network publication.

---

# 14. Publish Advertisements

After successful health verification:

* Advertisements SHALL be generated;
* Advertisements SHALL be signed;
* Advertisements SHALL be published;
* Heartbeats SHALL begin.

Publication SHALL occur only once startup has completed.

---

# 15. Ready State

The Hypervisor enters Ready when:

* all mandatory services are operational;
* startup tasks have completed;
* network publication has succeeded or is scheduled for retry.

The API SHALL begin accepting external requests only after entering Ready.

---

# 16. Failure Recovery

If startup fails:

* successfully started services SHALL shut down gracefully;
* resources SHALL be released;
* partial state SHALL remain recoverable.

The Hypervisor SHALL never continue in a partially initialized state.

---

# 17. Shutdown Sequence

Shutdown SHALL occur in reverse startup order.

